I've decided to do only minimal surgery on the patch, so now the code looks
like:

size = align1(size);
if (size != 0) {
  while (size >= 4096) {
    size -= 4096;
    SP -= 4096;
    *SP = XXX;
  }
  SP -= size;
  SP = align2(SP);
  *SP = XXX;
}

The various aligns in there are pre-existing.  They just weren't
effective, because zero is already aligned to everything.  So the word-sized
writes are okay, but only after checking if anything was allocated at all.

(In reply to Andreas Schwab from comment #5)
> Libc locks are simple (recursive) mutexes,

That's what I thought (or at least the current rtld locks).  But libc (libpthread) does provide read/write locks, right?  And they do provide
performance improvements over normal locks in mostly-read scenarios?  If so
those locks, and not the normal ones should be used for the dl_load_write_lock.

> if you need finer graned locking
> you need to use separate locks.

No, this is not about fine graned.  It's about this situation:

-------------------------
int global;
L lock;
int heavily_called(void) {
  LOCK_FOR_READ(lock);
  int ret = global;
  UNLOCK_FOR_READ(lock);
  return ret;
}

void seldom_called(int i) {
  LOCK_FOR_WRITE(lock);
  global = i;
  UNLOCK_FOR_WRITE(lock);
}
--------------------------

In this situation there's no finer grain than the above.  Nevertheless if
heavily_called is called from many threads simultaneously, while seldom_called
only once in a while or never, you'll get a huge speedup if L is a read/write
lock type (and {UN,}LOCK_FOR_{READ_WRITE} properly defined), and not just a
normal mutex.

If it's a normal mutex all calls to heavily_called() are synchronized (and will
often involve a kernel syscall if indeed multiple calls are active from different threads), while if it's a read/write lock they'll run concurrently
and usually won't synchronize with anything (except if a call to seldom_called()
intervenes).

(In reply to Michael Matz from comment #8)
> Ah, yes, I see.  Using it for the dl_load_write_lock would most probably help
> this specific use case quite some.  Would be cool to work on getting the
> infrastructure in place for this.

As I said.

Another probably quicker thing to try would be to iterate the single phdr
that never changes (for the executable) without any locking.  OTOH the
callback data includes GL(dl_load_adds) - nloaded whose computation involves
walking the whole linker map...  But that computation looks odd given it
does

  size_t nloaded = GL(dl_ns)[0]._ns_nloaded;
  Lmid_t ns = 0;
#ifdef SHARED
  const void *caller = RETURN_ADDRESS (0);
  for (Lmid_t cnt = GL(dl_nns) - 1; cnt > 0; --cnt)
    for (struct link_map *l = GL(dl_ns)[cnt]._ns_loaded; l; l = l->l_next)
      {
        /* We have to count the total number of loaded objects.  */
        nloaded += GL(dl_ns)[cnt]._ns_nloaded;

        if (caller >= (const void *) l->l_map_start
            && caller < (const void *) l->l_map_end
            && (l->l_contiguous
                || _dl_addr_inside_object (l, (ElfW(Addr)) caller)))
          ns = cnt;
      }
#endif

thus add GL(dl_ns)[0]._ns_nloaded once but GL(dl_ns)[cnt]._ns_nloaded as
many times as the size of the _ns_loaded list is long...

If the above walk ever becomes a bottleneck we can finish it after 'ns = cnt'
is found as well (just completing the nloaded computation).  That would also
make it useful to include ns 0 in the search (as that'll likely hit, the
optimization would be only to skip the search for dl_nns == 1).

So as we pass in state of the whole set of phrds skipping the locking
for GL(dl_ns)[0]._ns_loaded isn't going to work I guess.

As said elsewhere best performance would need a different interface used
by the unwinder, possibly one not iterating over all phdrs but just returning
the one with the affected address.  Even the glibc internal unwind functions
do not exploit this end use dl_iterate_phdr... (not that we are using those).


